WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.185 --> 00:00:00.725
Hey everyone.

2
00:00:00.775 --> 00:00:03.485
Today we're jumping right into the world of voice control,

3
00:00:03.705 --> 00:00:06.525
and it all boils down to one super simple idea.

4
00:00:06.795 --> 00:00:08.645
What you see on a screen, you should be able

5
00:00:08.645 --> 00:00:09.725
to say to control it.

6
00:00:10.085 --> 00:00:11.885
I mean, that sounds totally obvious, doesn't it?

7
00:00:12.025 --> 00:00:13.805
But you'd be surprised how often this

8
00:00:13.805 --> 00:00:15.005
very simple rule gets broken.

9
00:00:15.305 --> 00:00:18.925
So today we're gonna find out why. So let's set the scene.

10
00:00:19.645 --> 00:00:21.125
A user is looking at a website.

11
00:00:21.155 --> 00:00:23.685
They see a button, it says, search right on it.

12
00:00:23.785 --> 00:00:26.085
So they give the command, click search.

13
00:00:27.645 --> 00:00:31.445
And nothing, just silence.

14
00:00:32.475 --> 00:00:34.405
This isn't just some random bug, you know,

15
00:00:34.715 --> 00:00:36.685
it's a fundamental design flaw.

16
00:00:36.745 --> 00:00:38.085
And we're about to play detective

17
00:00:38.085 --> 00:00:41.685
and find out exactly what's going on here. Okay? So

18
00:00:41.685 --> 00:00:42.685
First things first. Who

19
00:00:42.685 --> 00:00:44.005
are we even talking about?

20
00:00:44.395 --> 00:00:45.885
It's really important to get this right.

21
00:00:46.295 --> 00:00:49.045
Voice control is not for people who can't see the screen.

22
00:00:49.145 --> 00:00:50.245
That's a totally different

23
00:00:50.245 --> 00:00:51.525
technology called a screen reader.

24
00:00:51.795 --> 00:00:53.005
Nope. This is for users

25
00:00:53.105 --> 00:00:54.845
who can see the screen perfectly well,

26
00:00:55.065 --> 00:00:56.765
but maybe they have a motor disability,

27
00:00:56.925 --> 00:00:58.405
A Repetitive strain injury,

28
00:00:58.625 --> 00:01:00.885
or even just a temporary thing, like a broken arm

29
00:01:01.385 --> 00:01:03.965
for them using a mouse or keyboard isn't reliable.

30
00:01:04.425 --> 00:01:06.605
So voice, that's their primary way in.

31
00:01:07.075 --> 00:01:09.565
Alright, time for our investigation to begin.

32
00:01:09.945 --> 00:01:11.565
And the whole mystery really comes down to this.

33
00:01:11.635 --> 00:01:14.485
There's a huge disconnect between the screen that we see

34
00:01:14.485 --> 00:01:16.605
with our eyes and the screen

35
00:01:16.605 --> 00:01:19.005
that the technology actually reads from under the hood.

36
00:01:19.465 --> 00:01:22.725
And boom, here is our first big clue on the left.

37
00:01:22.865 --> 00:01:24.085
That's what we all see, right?

38
00:01:24.485 --> 00:01:27.725
A button that clearly says search, but here's the kicker.

39
00:01:28.095 --> 00:01:30.285
Voice control doesn't look at the pixels on the screen.

40
00:01:30.795 --> 00:01:33.165
Instead it reads this sort of hidden map

41
00:01:33.165 --> 00:01:35.685
of the interface called the accessibility tree.

42
00:01:36.145 --> 00:01:37.925
And if you look at that map on the right,

43
00:01:38.305 --> 00:01:41.925
the button's real name isn't search, it's find products.

44
00:01:42.385 --> 00:01:45.245
So when our user says click search, the system is like,

45
00:01:45.255 --> 00:01:46.885
sorry, I have no idea what you're talking about.

46
00:01:47.065 --> 00:01:50.205
And the command fails. So what's a user supposed to do then?

47
00:01:50.915 --> 00:01:52.205
Well, they've got a few options,

48
00:01:52.265 --> 00:01:54.085
but honestly, they're not great.

49
00:01:54.705 --> 00:01:57.725
The best way, the ideal path is name based targeting.

50
00:01:57.945 --> 00:02:00.525
You just say what you see, click submit simple.

51
00:02:01.065 --> 00:02:02.405
But when that fails, they have

52
00:02:02.405 --> 00:02:03.845
to use these clunky workarounds.

53
00:02:04.225 --> 00:02:06.325
The next best thing is to say, show numbers.

54
00:02:06.705 --> 00:02:08.485
And the whole screen gets covered with little numbers.

55
00:02:08.995 --> 00:02:10.565
Then they have to scan for the right one

56
00:02:10.565 --> 00:02:11.765
and say, click seven.

57
00:02:12.435 --> 00:02:15.205
It's slow. And the last resort is a grid overlay,

58
00:02:15.205 --> 00:02:16.365
which is even more tedious.

59
00:02:16.905 --> 00:02:19.165
So you can see why our goal as designers is to make

60
00:02:19.165 --> 00:02:21.805
that first fast path work every single time.

61
00:02:22.425 --> 00:02:25.885
But hey, here's the good news. These failures aren't random.

62
00:02:26.075 --> 00:02:29.005
They're caused by a set of really common, predictable,

63
00:02:29.065 --> 00:02:31.485
and totally preventable design mistakes.

64
00:02:31.745 --> 00:02:33.965
So let's meet the usual suspects,

65
00:02:34.785 --> 00:02:38.365
and here they are, our six design saboteurs.

66
00:02:38.695 --> 00:02:40.685
We've got things like missing names, you know,

67
00:02:40.705 --> 00:02:42.965
for those little icon only buttons with no text

68
00:02:43.505 --> 00:02:44.645
or duplicate names

69
00:02:44.735 --> 00:02:46.725
where there are 10 different buttons on the page

70
00:02:46.725 --> 00:02:48.325
and they're all called learn more.

71
00:02:49.015 --> 00:02:50.685
Super helpful, right? And of course,

72
00:02:50.705 --> 00:02:52.605
the one we just caught in the act, the label

73
00:02:52.665 --> 00:02:55.325
and name mismatch where what a button says it's called

74
00:02:55.345 --> 00:02:57.525
and what it's actually called in the code are two

75
00:02:57.555 --> 00:02:58.765
totally different things.

76
00:02:59.585 --> 00:03:00.885
And this brings us right back

77
00:03:00.885 --> 00:03:02.445
to our original mystery, doesn't it?

78
00:03:02.445 --> 00:03:03.965
Because out of all these problems,

79
00:03:04.065 --> 00:03:05.565
the label in name mis math is

80
00:03:05.565 --> 00:03:07.685
by far the most frustrating for a user.

81
00:03:08.185 --> 00:03:09.245
And you can see why, right?

82
00:03:09.475 --> 00:03:11.165
They can see exactly what they wanna do.

83
00:03:11.305 --> 00:03:12.845
The interface looks perfectly clear,

84
00:03:13.065 --> 00:03:15.365
but when they speak the obvious command, it's like talking

85
00:03:15.365 --> 00:03:16.365
to a brick wall.

86
00:03:17.245 --> 00:03:18.285
Absolutely maddening.

87
00:03:19.025 --> 00:03:21.435
Okay, enough doom and gloom about the problems.

88
00:03:21.805 --> 00:03:23.355
Let's talk about the solution

89
00:03:23.465 --> 00:03:26.355
because it's actually really elegant, it's super simple,

90
00:03:26.655 --> 00:03:28.195
and it's a rule that every single

91
00:03:28.475 --> 00:03:29.635
designer should know by heart.

92
00:03:30.255 --> 00:03:31.795
And hey, this isn't just a good idea.

93
00:03:32.105 --> 00:03:34.155
It's an official web accessibility standard.

94
00:03:34.505 --> 00:03:36.235
It's called label and name.

95
00:03:36.615 --> 00:03:39.475
And it was created specifically to solve this exact problem.

96
00:03:39.905 --> 00:03:42.315
It's considered a baseline level a requirement,

97
00:03:42.445 --> 00:03:44.075
which means it's one of the most fundamental

98
00:03:44.075 --> 00:03:45.395
things you need to get right?

99
00:03:46.255 --> 00:03:47.755
So let's just translate

100
00:03:47.755 --> 00:03:49.755
that technical jargon into plain English.

101
00:03:50.065 --> 00:03:53.075
It's this, If a button or a link or any

102
00:03:53.075 --> 00:03:55.875
Control has visible text on it, then the

103
00:03:55.875 --> 00:03:57.235
Accessible name, the one in that

104
00:03:57.235 --> 00:03:59.515
Hidden map we talked about must include that

105
00:03:59.515 --> 00:04:01.235
Exact same text. That's it.

106
00:04:01.465 --> 00:04:02.555
It's really that simple.

107
00:04:03.295 --> 00:04:05.435
And this table just makes it crystal clear.

108
00:04:05.855 --> 00:04:07.115
If the button says submit,

109
00:04:07.135 --> 00:04:10.075
and its name is submit order, that passes the name,

110
00:04:10.075 --> 00:04:11.635
contains the visible text.

111
00:04:11.945 --> 00:04:15.115
Perfect. Same for close and close dialogue.

112
00:04:15.655 --> 00:04:17.555
But then look at our original problem.

113
00:04:18.055 --> 00:04:19.515
The visible text is search,

114
00:04:19.655 --> 00:04:21.755
but the accessible name is find products.

115
00:04:21.935 --> 00:04:24.995
That's a fail. The word search is nowhere to be found.

116
00:04:25.665 --> 00:04:27.155
Okay, so we get the rule,

117
00:04:27.455 --> 00:04:29.395
but how do we actually put this into practice?

118
00:04:29.885 --> 00:04:32.235
Let's get into a clear, actionable playbook

119
00:04:32.505 --> 00:04:33.875
that every designer can use

120
00:04:33.875 --> 00:04:35.475
to get this right every single time.

121
00:04:36.105 --> 00:04:39.435
Here it is your five step workflow. Step one is easy.

122
00:04:39.665 --> 00:04:42.395
Your visible label is your baseline accessible name.

123
00:04:42.945 --> 00:04:45.195
Step two, if you really need to add more context,

124
00:04:45.425 --> 00:04:47.795
just make sure the full name starts with a visible text.

125
00:04:48.385 --> 00:04:50.435
Step three, write this stuff down,

126
00:04:50.755 --> 00:04:52.355
annotate it in your design specs.

127
00:04:52.745 --> 00:04:55.155
Step four, talk about it during your design reviews.

128
00:04:55.535 --> 00:04:58.715
And step five, and this is the big one, test it yourself.

129
00:04:58.985 --> 00:05:00.035
Turn on voice control

130
00:05:00.035 --> 00:05:02.035
and see if you can truly say what you see.

131
00:05:02.695 --> 00:05:04.835
You know, when you boil it all down, it comes back

132
00:05:04.835 --> 00:05:06.035
to this one powerful

133
00:05:06.225 --> 00:05:07.355
Idea. The

134
00:05:07.355 --> 00:05:09.715
Words you choose as a designer are not just

135
00:05:09.715 --> 00:05:11.075
static text on a screen.

136
00:05:11.425 --> 00:05:13.155
They become the actual commands your

137
00:05:13.155 --> 00:05:14.355
users speak to get around.

138
00:05:15.055 --> 00:05:17.155
You are Directly in control of that experience,

139
00:05:17.575 --> 00:05:18.995
and that's a huge responsibility,

140
00:05:19.135 --> 00:05:20.955
but it's also a massive opportunity

141
00:05:20.975 --> 00:05:23.475
to make things better. So I'll leave

142
00:05:23.475 --> 00:05:24.475
You with this question.

143
00:05:24.855 --> 00:05:27.715
You are the one writing the labels for every button,

144
00:05:27.925 --> 00:05:29.835
every link, every single field.

145
00:05:30.375 --> 00:05:32.755
So what are you going to empower your users to say?

146
00:05:33.135 --> 00:05:35.475
Are they gonna say click search and have it just work?

147
00:05:35.895 --> 00:05:37.915
Or will they be forced to say, show numbers,

148
00:05:38.535 --> 00:05:39.555
the choice is yours.
